description:
Currently, UCSF pager messaging user requests for MAC (Moves-Adds-Changes) services via IT Service-Now are supported by various UCSF IT departments and third-party vendors using multiple applications and their respective UI (User Interface) - (e.g., USA Mobility, Amcom, Pagerbox, Careweb & MSO).  These disparate applications often create database inconsistencies with respect to pager numbers and their associated user names.  There is no System of Record/Source of Truth for pager information.    
We need a strategy to automate and enhance pager request processes in place before next Summer 2018 (which is when ticket volume increases in support of new incoming Residents.)

description: REDCap Account Request: 1 new user account(s) requested.

Our current hardware for Cloverleaf running on the AIX for the West Bay is over 5 years old now. There are possible plans to look into moving off premise Linux support. Heidi has asked to look into combining the Cloverleaf processes between East and West Bay prior to combining Epic. There are possible partnership in the near future with other organizations such as Marin General that will use the Cloverleaf engine.  I am also told by Lisa Hunt that there is a line item in this years budget for 170K for interface server replacement.  I am following up with her to see if this can be carried forward to next fiscal year.  Cloverleaf is now owned by Infor.  I have started working with our Infor representative to start looking into the licensing portion of combining East and West Bay and also with partnering with Marin General.  Like to collaborate with Mo to start planning for the Cloverleaf hardware move.

Currently Hospitality has an Escalation Button that emails a group to let them know that the ticket needs attention.

-Escalation Button will create a dialogue box where customer can explain the reason for the escalation and that message will be sent along with the escalation. 
-Escalation Button will be available for all MCSS departments. (Facilities, Clinical Tech, Safety Office, Material Services, and Signage)
-Escalation Button will notify Pager Duty Alert to grab the attention of the correct People that need the escalation.
-Escalation Button will be available in all standard automated messages that go out to client in the email. For example, at the bottom of every email, there is a link that says, "If you would like to talk to someone about the status of the ticket or escalate the ticket issue, please click here"

description:
Administrative Contact: 
   Name: Michelle Ruiz
   Email: michelle.ruiz@ucsf.edu
   Phone: +1 415 502-8832


Request Details: 
   Requested By Date: 2018-02-12
   Overview/Business Requirement: For use with Salesforce Marketing Cloud:

University Development and Alumni relations is seeking to centralize our online email and social communications from Luminate Online (Convio), MailChimp, and iModules over to Salesforce Marketing Cloud (SFMC). SFMC will allow UDAR and its campus partners to create a more dynamic email marketing experience for donors and give them more relevant content that they are interested in. 

We would like to implement SSO so that UCSF UDAR employees can access this new platform with their UCSF MyAccess credentials. Benefits include:
- Quicker user adoption of the tool so they aren't having to remember one more login.
- Easier user management from the product team. As employees leave UCSF their access to this resource is contingent on them having an active UCSF employee account.
   Intended Use: IDs are used solely for user account login access to SFMC
   Security: Non-UCSF Data Center
   Required Attributes: 
      UCSFID: unique identifier represents the shared identifier between the identity provider and the Marketing Cloud to validate access

   Name: Karen Brungardt
   Email: Karen.Brungardt@ucsf.edu
   Phone: +1 415 514-3689


Request Details: 
   Requested By Date: 2018-03-02
   Overview/Business Requirement: Our solution, the Complion eRegulatory System, is a documentation and workflow solution that replaces a hybrid method in which electronic files are maintained in a redundant shared/network drive while the auditable copy is manually kept in paper regulatory binders. In order to allow physicians and others to electronically sign documents easily, Complion has integrated with standard authentication identity providers (IDP) to allow users to sign in to the Complion application.
   Intended Use: Our solution, the Complion eRegulatory System, is a documentation and workflow solution that replaces a hybrid method in which electronic files are maintained in a redundant shared/network drive while the auditable copy is manually kept in paper regulatory binders. In order to allow physicians and others to electronically sign documents easily, Complion has integrated with standard authentication identity providers (IDP) to allow users to sign in to the Complion application.
   Security: Non-UCSF Data Center
   Required Attributes: 
      UCSFID: need an attribute to link the user from UCSF to the user in Complion Enterprise. could be UCSF ID OR Email Address
      Email Addr: need an attribute to link the user from UCSF to the user in Complion Enterprise.could be UCSF ID OR Email Address

description: REDCap Account Request: 1 new user account(s) requested.
Customer will not be needing a new computer

Administrative Contact: 
   Name: Alex Siu
   Email: Alex.Siu@ucsf.edu
   Phone: +1 415 514-0970


Request Details: 
   Overview/Business Requirement: Qualtrics wants us to update our SSO metadata. We are already using UCSF SSO. I am submitting a request per Nathan's instructions. 

https://ucsf.qualtrics.com


Hi Alex.

It looks like Qualtrics is changing their SAML entityID.  To our system, this would appear to be a completely new integration, even though it may be the same application.  You'll want to fill out and submit a MyAccess Integration Request.  That form is at

	https://ucsf.service-now.com/ess/myaccess_request.do

In the description of the application on that form, please specify the entityID of the current Qualtrics SAML integration.  If you don't know that, provide the URL used to initiate a SSO login and I should be able to find the entityID in our configuration.

Regards,
Nathan
----
Nathan Sheldon
Systems Integration Engineer
    Identity and Access Management,
    Information Technology Services
University of California, San Francisco








On Feb 28, 2018, at 9:29 AM, Siu, Alex <Alex.Siu@ucsf.edu> wrote:

Hi Nathan,
 
Do you have any advice on how best to coordinate the SSO changes with our vendor Qualtrics?
 
Thanks.
 
From: Qualtrics Support [mailto:support@qualtrics.com] 
Sent: Wednesday, February 28, 2018 9:12 AM
To: Siu, Alex <Alex.Siu@ucsf.edu>
Cc: Leykin, Yan <Yan.Leykin@ucsf.edu>
Subject: RE: SSO login system migration for UCSF
 
Alex, 

We'll need to have your team apply our new metadata to your system: 

https://co1.qualtrics.com/login/v1/sso/saml2/metadata

If your team uses InCommon all they will need to do is start sending your attributes to the entity ID: https://co1.qualtrics.com

If your team uses Okta, I will give them a different set of instructions.

We'll need to decide on a specific date & time to have your team make the changes on their end and for me to implement the necessary changes on our end. Then we'll have someone log into their account to make sure everything is working smoothly. 

Best,
Sam Schmitz
SUPPORT

cat_item: ARF: Account Request Form (Campus, SOM, ZSFG/SFGH)

description: DSGYYM2

Over the past few months we have been working with the local data analytics firm, Tag.bio, to develop and test a new self-service cost data platform. This tool rapidly queries our inpatient EPSI financial data and offers multiple protocols reflecting common financial and utilization questions. The target audience for this platform is frontline initiative owners, improvement specialists, analysts, and clinicians with an interest in understanding costs and how they relate to improvement proposals. Within Value Improvement, we've used the platform to pull historical service line data for the recent leadership report outs and vet Caring Wisely proposal financial projections. Physicians with access have also begun using the tool during clinical practice to assess the cost of drugs, lab tests, etc. 
 	Other privacy/ risk issues? [Note:  Tag.bio completed the UCSF risk assessment in 2017 and is up for renewal in March 2018]

description:
Goal: Create a patient-facing mobile-first website that supports a matching interface with a static database (i.e. list of prostate clinical trial translated into patient-friendly features; until an actual API can be built for OnCore)

	Cost implications

description:

   Name: Carson Tam

Request Details: 
   Requested By Date: 2018-03-30
   Overview/Business Requirement: School of Pharmacy would like to host video lectures and resources on Panopto cloud service, and one of the business requirement is to have MyAccess SSO to the cloud service for seamless user experience.
   Intended Use: The data will be used to identify the user and log in to the system.
   Security: Non-UCSF Data Center
   Required Attributes: 
      UCSFID: To uniquely identify the user
      Name: To show user their own name
      Email Addr: To identify the user on the Panopto system
      ePPN: To uniquely identify the user

mNGS - Data Analysis and Website Server
To support our needs for our mNGS assay, we maintain local servers that perform data analysis and host our own-developed web application (SURPIviz). Our sample throughput is steadily increasing, and our goal is to streamline our workflows for interpretation and resulting to scale up our capacity. We ultimately want to improve upon our current web application to create our own clinical reports (PDF) and deliver the reports (via fax to outside institutions and scan to APEX/SQ for UCSF patients). To achieve this we need to be able to host PHI on our servers.

Tuan Nguyen, from LIS, mentioned that we would be able to use a virtual server with the medical center. It would be nice to know what are our options are to host locally compared to hosting a virtual server with the medical center (also potential costs and risks related to each). Lastly, additional information about establishing an interface with APEX and/or Sunquest would also be beneficial for our goals.

-There is a patient facing application and administrative application
-Both are Ruby on rails applications, the patient facing app using javascript
-It is currently hosted on a postgres database, although they may be able to facilitate changing the type needed requires both an application and database server

Our main concern would be costs to host TrakU on UCSF servers, costs for transferring site to server, and steps we would have to take to accomplish this. 

We (YAFC at UCSF) have been working with a development team  at Northwestern, but the developers/coordinators are leaving Northwestern so we need to transfer the app from their servers to UCSF.

cat_item: ARF: Account Request Form (Campus, SOM, ZSFG/SFGH)
ARF: Active Directory Resource Account Request (Campus only)

description:
Location: SFGH
1. desktop16GB  4740YM2

Hi Chris,
I have questions,and at yesterday's meeting I was reminded that I do know someone to ask - you!

Over the years I've learned various, contradictory lessons about how our AV devices work best on various segments of the UCSF network. 

1)	In 2014 Mission Bay IT teams and I learned that the secure wireless roaming functionality provided by UCSFwpa cannot be made compatible with Bonjour, the service used by Apple TVs to broadcast their presence. Too bad, because lots of people were counting on Airplay at that time, and the AV vendor provided dozens and dozens of extra devices that were unusable. However, over the last 2 years I've noticed that APPLE TVs work just fine, no matter where I put em. How can I gain confidence that the network will continue to support these? 
2)	I remember this as well.  I think we can broach this topic with Manish Sompura and see what he says now vs back then.

2) Networked AV systems have been maturing for a few years now, and it's mighty tempting to use this technology - maybe in the MS-1112 room or maybe in the Clinical Sciences classrooms and conference rooms.  How I could make sure a networked AV system would live happily on the UCSF network ?

Here is an example:
https://www.crestron.com/Products/Featured-Solutions/DigitalMedia-NVX-Series
	For this I would also recommend we just model it out for Manish in terms of network requirements.  Can you put together a quick sketch of the user case and how much bandwidth it would require?  We can then have a conversation with Manish and inform him of the plan.

3) I've already deployed a few Dante systems - this is networked audio which uses less bandwidth than audio plus video, and supports non-critical functionality in my rooms. These designs use a small Cisco POE switch located in the AV Rack. I understand that this may be frowned upon, but I've never found it written down anywhere, and I've never been denied service or alerted by IT Security, so I'm getting more comfortable/reliant on throwing switches into the AV racks. 
Any thoughts?
	It is looking like all roads lead back to the network team and Manish specifically.  I've seen this setup in AV racks as well and I don't think it would be breaking any rules to do it.  I think we would just want to have the device registered.  Again another line item to review with Manish.

Let me know when you have the above info together and I can reach out to Manish and setup the conversation.


thanks for your  thoughts,

Henry Kyburg
AV Engineer/ETS 
415-502-7188

description:
Forwarded email from Bobby Cusack to Jann Fong;
Luci Frias gave me your name. I am working for ATOM which now rents space from BIohub in 499 Illinois on the 4th floor. We will be moving to the second floor sometime in July and will have to implement our own IT. We are looking for 5GBPS and I have quoted out Comcast. I want to find out how much it would cost for UCSF to install and maintain our IT system on the second floor.  Would I work with you for that? How do I proceed. Another option we are considering is whether we should coordinate with UCSF IT on the 6th floor (piggy back). UCSF will be our landlord starting in July (currently it is Biohub). Thanks for your insights.Cheers,Deirdre  https://atomscience.org/

   Overview/Business Requirement: Our solution, the Complion eRegulatory System, is a documentation and workflow solution that replaces a hybrid method in which electronic files are maintained in a redundant shared/network drive while the auditable copy is manually kept in paper regulatory binders. cat_item: ARF: Account Request Form (Campus, SOM, ZSFG/SFGH)

description:
In order to alleviate the burden of documentation from our providers, we continue to explore different scribe vendors who can meet our demand and expectations. During our search, we met with Robin Healthcare who offers a virtual scribe solution. Their solution combines US-based virtual scribes with voice recognition and Artificial Intelligence. The latter 2 components are very important to us since we strongly believe that this is the direction that scribing is headed in. If successful, we can eventually eliminate the virtual scribe from the equation and have a completely AI/voice-recognition based solution to assist our physicians. This would significantly cut costs and could help the program offer the scribe resource on a larger scale.
 
Robin Healthcare supplies its clients with a cylindrical device that is placed into an exam room. The device, which has audio and visual capabilities, is able to document and perform various tasks based on the conversation in the exam room. An actual scribe will then log in remotely to review the note, make any edits, and submit directly into APeX. The physician will then have to sign into APeX, review the scribe's submission and sign the encounter.
 
According to Robin, they "use 256-bit military-grade encryption" and they assure their clients that "all data is encrypted both at rest and in transit" in a HIPAA compliant manner.

description:
We need to replace the physical server QCCREDWDB002 as the hardware is out of warranty. 
I'm requesting a VM named QCCREDWDB003 with 8 CPU, 48GB ram with a 32GB reservation, and 120gb of "local" disk for the OS drive, and at least a 10gb network connection. 

The database on QCCREDWDB002 is currently using approx 3.5TB of SAN storage and we would re-use this on QCCREDWDB003.
Can we transfer our existing SQL server license from QCCREDWDB002 to QCCREDWDB003? 

Added 05/30/2018: To be clear, do not disconnect the existing SAN storage on QCCREDWDB002. QCCREDWDB003 initially only requires 120gb of "local" disk for the OS and MS SQL Server installation. 

Edit 06/01/2018: Please add the following disks on SAN storage to QCCREDWDB003 when it is built
G:	1 TB		Database
H:	200 GB	Logs
I:	1 TB		stage/backups

description:
Hello! My name is Miriam Muscarella and I am a 4th year medical student at UCSF.  I am working on a qualitative study involving interviews with past patients at UCSF's Center for Reproductive Health with Dr. Lauri Pasch (cc'ed) from the Department of Psychiatry and Psychology and Fellow Dr. Eleni Greenberg in OBGYN's REI division. 
We are interested in using Zoom to conduct our interviews and had a few questions with SOM Technology Services
First: what are the security needs in order to audio record (and store) conversations through Zoom? As investigators, we would of course have our computers encrypted, but what are the requirements for potential patient participants speaking from home? Does Zoom and Zoom storage of audio/video meet UCSF research requirements?
Second: we have already reached out to the Zoom representative at UCSF as well as the IRB office, and they suggested we reach out to IT Services to better understand the safety requirements for Zoom and its use for research.

description:
GitHub @ UCSF:

Proposal for the UCSF CRT (IT governance committee for research technology) to implement a central code sharing platform for UCSF teams that develop software code:

From: "Gologorskaya, Oksana" <Oksana.Gologorskaya@ucsf.edu>
Date: Thursday, May 10, 2018 at 1:57 PM
To: "Israni, Sharat" <Sharat.Israni@ucsf.edu>, "Larsen, Rick" <Rick.Larsen@ucsf.edu>, "Pletcher, Mark" <mpletcher@epi.ucsf.edu>, "Yuan, Leslie" <leslie.yuan@ucsf.edu>, "Creasman, Jennifer" <Jennifer.Creasman@ucsf.edu>, "Wang, Michael" <Michael.Wang4@ucsf.edu>, "Lindquist, Karla" <Karla.Lindquist@ucsf.edu>, "Noor, Zeanid" <Zeanid.Noor@ucsf.edu>
Cc: "Lam, Jamie" <Jamie.Lam@ucsf.edu>, "Buenaventura, Ana" <Ana.Buenaventura@ucsf.edu>, "Harris, Mattice F" <Mattice.Harris@ucsf.edu>, "Hearne, Quinn" <Quinn.Hearne@ucsf.edu>, "Berrean, Beth" <Beth.Berrean@ucsf.edu>
Subject: GitHub at UCSF - CRT Proposal - Early Adopters Input/Support Needed
 
Hi All,
 
I am part of a cross-disciplinary group (CC-d) working on a proposal for the UCSF CRT (IT governance committee for research technology) to implement a central code sharing platform for UCSF teams that develop software code. Benefits of having a centrally managed platform include increased developer productivity, improved knowledge sharing, consistent code management process and minimized privacy and security risks.
 
Minimizing privacy and security risks associated with sharing code is a key requirement for campus-wide code sharing platform because the code written for biomedical applications may involve accessing and processing clinical data and other proprietary information. 
 
We are looking at GitHub as one of the best currently available solutions. Our top 2 implementation options include on-premise hosting and AWS-based hosting. 
 
We are asking you as the informatics/technology program leaders to support this proposal and help us present the business case with the 2 following steps:
1.	Confirm your program has a high priority need for secure code sharing platform and let us know how many of your team members would actively use it in the first 1-2 years.
2.	Consider sharing the implementation cost with the IT Governance CRT. Perhaps, splitting half of the deployment and first year administration cost among 3-4 early adopters would make this proposal more feasible for funding. We don't have  final cost estimates yet, but we will be able to share them in the next 2-3 weeks.
Please let us know your general thoughts on 1,2, by May 23, assuming the shared cost would be feasible for your budget. 
We are hoping to get this proposal on CRT agenda in June-July. 
 
Thank you!
Oksana

description: REDCap Account Request: 1 new user account(s) requested.
Tableau for Public Dashboards

Wondering if we could set up a time to talk BEFORE we implement anything!
My free times are listed at www.doodle.com/stevenchanmd  -- feel free to propose a couple of times.

At the moment, AC3 (the APeX Clinical Content Committee) -- run by Kelsey Sobomehin, Andy Auerbach, and Kay Burke -- approves "BestPractice Advisory" alerts, but unified documentation does not exist for these items. ServiceNow currently contains tickets for only a portion of these alerts.

We were wondering if we can use ServiceNow such that a special type of "ticket" acts as this unified documentation ... perhaps similar to http://itsm.ucsf.edu/sites/itsm.ucsf.edu/files/qrc_-_knowledge_management.pdf (Knowledge Management).


We could set up ServiceNow so there are "master tickets" / "master issues" / "parent tickets". 1 Parent Ticket represents 1 BPA.

    RITM0012804 Master: BPA D-Dimer
    RITM00123554 Master: BPA Concierge Pop-up
    RITM012345 Master: BPA Palliative Care Screen

Then, any new requests, single incidents, build requests would be child tickets:

    RITM0012804 Master: BPA D-Dimer (open, because this is active)
        RITM213131 Child: Initial build (resolved)
        RITM213132 Child: Second update (resolved)
        RITM213133 Child: Active request (open ticket)
    RITM00123554 Master: BPA Concierge Pop-up
        ... etc...
    RITM012345 Master: BPA Palliative Care Screen
        ... etc...

Within each Master/Parent Ticket, we can post info like statistics, descriptions, etc. 


Please let me know how we can set this up!


Thanks,
Steven Chan, MD MBA
UCSF Health Clinical Informatics fellow
